# VARIABLE
  A variable is a name used to store data in memory. It acts like a container that holds values.

# Syntax :
variable_name = value

# Eg :
name = "John"

# Multiple Variable Assignment :
x, y, z = 10, 20, 30
a = b = c = 100

# Rules for Naming Variables
  In Python, there are certain rules to name a variable. They are 

  Variable names can contain:
    •Letters (A-Z, a-z)
    •Numbers (0-9)
    •Underscore (_)
  
  Variable names must start with:
    •A letter
    •An underscore (_)
  
  Variable names cannot:
    •Start with a number
    •Contain spaces
    •Use special symbols like @, #, $, %

# Printing Variables :
  Use the print() function.

# Eg 1:
name = "John"
print(name)

# Eg 2:
name = "John"
age = 21
print("Name:", name)
print("Age:", age)

# Eg 3:
name = "John"
age = 21
print(f"My name is {name} and I am {age} years old.")

# Getting Input from User
  Use the input() function.

1. String Input (str)
name = input("Enter your name: ")
print(f"Name: {name}")

2. Integer Input (int)
age = int(input("Enter your age: "))
print(f"Age: {age}")

3. Float Input (float)
cgpa = float(input("Enter your CGPA: "))
print(f"CGPA: {cgpa}")
print(type(cgpa))

4. Boolean Input (bool)
  Since input() gives a string, a common way is:

value = input("Enter True or False: ")
is_valid = value == "True"
print(f"Value: {is_valid}")


5. Taking Multiple Inputs
name = input("Enter Name: ")
age = int(input("Enter Age: "))
cgpa = float(input("Enter CGPA: "))

print(f"Name: {name}")
print(f"Age: {age}")
print(f"CGPA: {cgpa}")

#Variable Reassignment
  The value of a variable can be changed.

#Eg :
age = 20
print(age)
age = 21
print(age)

